# @rainbowindex/postcss

PostCSS plugin for Rainbow Index.

Use this integration when your build tool already has PostCSS in its pipeline—Webpack, Next.js, Parcel, and others. If
you're using Vite, the dedicated [Vite plugin](./../vite) provides better HMR support.

## Installation

```bash
npm install rainbowindex @rainbowindex/postcss postcss
```

## Usage

### PostCSS Config

```js
// postcss.config.js
import rainbowindex from "@rainbowindex/postcss";

export default {
    plugins: [rainbowindex()],
};
```

### With Build Tools

**Webpack:**

```js
// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
    module: {
        rules: [
            {
                test: /\.css$/,
                use: [
                    "style-loader",
                    "css-loader",
                    {
                        loader: "postcss-loader",
                        options: {
                            postcssOptions: {
                                plugins: [require("@rainbowindex/postcss")()],
                            },
                        },
                    },
                ],
            },
        ],
    },
};
```

**Next.js:**

```js
// postcss.config.js
module.exports = {
    plugins: {
        "@rainbowindex/postcss": {},
    },
};
```

## Options

```typescript
interface RainbowIndexOptions {
    /** Base directory for resolving source files */
    base?: string;
    /** Source file patterns to scan for utility classes */
    content?: string[];
    /** Optimize the output CSS */
    optimize?: boolean | { minify?: boolean };
}
```

### Examples

```js
// Default options
rainbowindex();

// Custom content patterns
rainbowindex({
    content: ["./src/**/*.tsx", "./components/**/*.tsx"],
});

// Disable optimization
rainbowindex({
    optimize: false,
});

// Optimize but don't minify
rainbowindex({
    optimize: { minify: false },
});

// Custom base directory
rainbowindex({
    base: "./packages/app",
});
```

## CSS Setup

Create your main CSS file:

```css
/* src/index.css */
@import "rainbowindex";

@theme {
    --color-primary: oklch(0.6 0.2 250);
}

/* Add Google Fonts with automatic theme configuration */
@font "Inter" from google {
    weights: 400, 500, 600, 700;
    set: sans; /* Automatically configures --font-sans */
}
```

The `@font` directive with `set:` handles font loading and theme variable configuration in one step—no need to manually
define `--font-sans` in `@theme`.

## How It Works

The plugin scans your source files for utility class names, compiles detected utilities into CSS, and optionally
optimizes with Lightning CSS. It reports file dependencies to PostCSS for proper watch mode support.

## File Dependencies

The plugin automatically reports file dependencies to PostCSS, enabling proper watch mode:

- Source files scanned for classes
- Imported CSS files
- The input CSS file

## Default Content Patterns

If no `content` option is provided, the plugin automatically detects common project structures:

- `src/**/*.{tsx,jsx,ts,js,html,vue,svelte}` (if `src/` exists)
- `app/**/*.{tsx,jsx,ts,js,html,vue,svelte}` (if `app/` exists)
- `pages/**/*.{tsx,jsx,ts,js,html,vue,svelte}` (if `pages/` exists)
- `components/**/*.{tsx,jsx,ts,js,html,vue,svelte}` (if `components/` exists)

